### Template Functions

Function templates allow writing a single function definition that works with different data types.

---

### Basic Function Template

```cpp
template <typename T>
T add(T a, T b) {
  return a + b;
}

int main() {
  cout << add(5, 3);        // T deduced as int
  cout << add(2.5, 1.5);    // T deduced as double
}
```

---

### Multiple Template Parameters

```cpp
template <typename T, typename U>
auto multiply(T a, U b) -> decltype(a * b) {  // Trailing return type
  return a * b;
}

// C++14: auto deduction
// C++11: decltype(auto) or trailing return type
```

---

### Explicit Template Arguments

```cpp
template <typename T>
T castTo(double value) {
  return static_cast<T>(value);
}

int x = castTo<int>(3.14);        // Explicit: T = int
double y = castTo<double>(3.14);  // Explicit: T = double
```

---

### Abbreviated Function Templates (C++20)

```cpp
auto add(auto a, auto b) {  // Equivalent to template
  return a + b;
}
```

---

### Function Template Overloading

```cpp
template <typename T>
void print(T value) {
  cout << value << endl;
}

template <typename T>
void print(T value, int precision) {
  cout.precision(precision);
  cout << fixed << value << endl;
}

void print(const char* value) {
  cout << "String: " << value << endl;
}
```

---

> **Key Point:** The compiler deduces template arguments from function arguments. Use explicit arguments when deduction is ambiguous or when you need a specific instantiation.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

template <typename T>
void swapValues(T& a, T& b) {
  T temp = a;
  a = b;
  b = temp;
}

int main() {
  int x = 10, y = 20;
  swapValues(x, y);
  cout << "x=" << x << " y=" << y << endl;

  string s1 = "hello", s2 = "world";
  swapValues(s1, s2);
  cout << "s1=" << s1 << " s2=" << s2 << endl;
  return 0;
}
